cs.SI, cs.SD, cs.SOC, cs.CL, cs.CY 

This paper is likely to belong to the following arXiv CS sub-categories: 

1. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper uses a network approach to analyse the Twitter activity around the Occupy Wall Street movement, focusing on the interactions between human communication activity and semantic content. 

2. cs.SD (Software Development and Programming) - The paper does not directly focus on software development or programming, but it does use computational methods to analyse the Twitter data. 

3. cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) - The paper is concerned with the social movement of Occupy Wall Street and the social networks that developed around it. 

4. cs.CL (Computation and Language) - The paper uses natural language processing techniques to analyse the semantic content of the Twitter data. 

5. cs.CY (Computers and Society) - The paper is concerned with the intersection of technology and society, specifically the role of social media in political movements.
